<b>Earnshaw Cook</b> (born <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../347/19347.xml">
March 28</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../653/34653.xml">
1900</link> in <village wordnetid="108672738" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../359/116359.xml">
Reisterstown, Maryland</link></village>
 - died <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../447/21447.xml">
November 11</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../760/34760.xml">
1987</link> in <village wordnetid="108672738" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../582/36582.xml">
Baltimore, Maryland</link></village>
) was an early researcher and proponent of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../692/28692.xml">
sabermetrics</link>, the analysis of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../850/3850.xml">
baseball</link> through <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../ium/4th_millennium.xml">
statistical</link> means.
<sec>
<st>
